Parliament did not ratify the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected on second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing the penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the door to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for entering into an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court is due to rule on the convicted woman’s appeal in December.
Tymosenko describes the ruling as political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court also in the west.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
