The diet of an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes cold cuts for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, 9% of schoolchildren are above average in weight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, sausages are found 50% more often than in families of normal-weight children.
19% of the obese had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of small big ones sport is also not a habit, which is now the case with most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Investigation of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third grade have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of children who are overweight or even obese is the lack of proper diet and not enough physical exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed say they eat for example breakfast five times a day – in case – lunch – snack – dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” one of the results of the survey said.
No breakfast and cold cuts at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
And the worst thing that has been reported is that one-tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
However, breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy french fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student – not to mention weight – drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned exercise regularly but for the parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diets based on possibilities proposed according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are lots of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is a great preference for sweet lemonades," the results of the survey said.
For lunch it was pasta that took the first place right in front of white meat.
The children did not want at all starchy and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading on health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a control of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session 'Obesity is not a coincidence', there was a well-determined desire to move towards a healthy diet," the results of the survey indicate.
The most striking was for example with regard to sweet lemonades because children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked on the questionnaire the white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce the sweet dishes and the "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread flour or potato dumplings).
