How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a tilt to the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not permitted for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West however you had to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was however not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The travels of the Czechs have since 1989 experienced a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at the maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holiday days in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of the Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in western neighbouring countries led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a boarding house.
The typical trait of a Czech trip at that time was to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary have increased which caused another important moment around the year 1997.
Thanks to an increasing demand for travel travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with routes by air charters which thanks to contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what there was before.
At the end of the 90s the Czechs had visa-free connections with practically most developed countries around the world except the US which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to rank completely in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for a holiday abroad including ancillary charges. Crowns per person.
