21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion that Moved
Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with highs, lows and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, glass sheds, bright and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the World's Fair in Brussels in 1958 is a good example of this.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its light and suspended steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered to this day as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World's Fair.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His project of pavilion as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the train station of the south of Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang works of art, so not a good environment.
However it was used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has deteriorated more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvedere museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every respect.
The new start was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, who promoted an art historian to a considerable career among other things in her youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she particularly carried out the work of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a cafe and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, low budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensibly transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following his travel to Vienna and by its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a pit of energy," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was laid and the roof replaced with a special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges were reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings were rehabilitated.
Two basements have made way for the new farm, a dimmed light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but still the lightweight Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remained, the house is painted in a protective shade against rust of red-brown color.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also please the office of protection monuments," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, “which came from Brussels,” said Krischanitz recently, a typical “Drop-in-the-City” story.
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a lucky shot of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the newly planned "quarter of the central station", with offices and apartments.
And maybe another stroke of luck will happen: the House of the 21st century could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
