Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He has written here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It has a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; hardly any ambassadors or discussions on strategies and materials are found.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he says, as a "book describing what it might look like," with "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods."
"Beauty and Sorrow" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and vendors.
Some will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war, some will lose limbs, go crazy, or lose their lives.
Their lives falter here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund’s book deviates from traditional history books.
He denies the idea that the First World War can only be summed up in the terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skilfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
