7 Lessons From Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford – distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recent interview with Steve Jobs that will air this week in the first part of a movie on major markets, is how much that creative mind had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart improver - a man who believed that many business executives were suffering from a "disease that lets them think that a great idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of great work separates a handbook from a great idea.
In 1995, Bob Cringley developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years since Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringley is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in the transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video was found in the director’s garage.
This video, slightly uplifted, is the basis of the 68-minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released in cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday next.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs weighs his thoughts clearly, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringley’s questions, giving him elbows to speed him up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, we find a strangely insightful aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision on the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He then explains them and then puts them into practice.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable Lost Interview sequences:
On how he learned to run a business:
“All these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to elaborate on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" assessed by the nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated plant that guaranteed accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a round to the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the “Blue Box” he created with Steve Wozniak – a device that was used to hack phone networks and make free long-distance phone calls.
The device has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We’d wrap the ball around different things half a dozen times and you’d scream in the pay phone and it’d happen a minute later on the pay phone next door,” Jobs said, laughing.
“We were young and with this Blue Box we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't both know much, but we invented a little thing that could control great things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to tell a wonderful story that he and Wozniak have devised: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go insane laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett’s drive):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP’s employees to visit the company’s research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first desktop computer ever designed.”
He was as big as a suitcase, he had a small cathode-ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
The Improvisation of Innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a whim.
Early in his career, as he sets up to sell some PCBs, a client asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working for only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that proved incredibly reliable.
On large companies that are running out of steam:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you worked at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [these are the types of people] who end up leading companies and product specialists are put away from decision-making.
The genius in product that led to this position of monopoly is completely rotted by people who can’t imagine designing a good product versus a bad product – the manual work required.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire IT industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They wrestled defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge piece of manual work separates a great idea from an outstanding product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to be made...Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made for personal taste. It's about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product that you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists fly.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
That's part of what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who just proved to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
