How to Spot a Lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how ubiquitous cheating and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has passed himself off as an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers have given test answers to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout, "I got you," deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research into such projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the findings of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They do not stutter, blush, or get agitated all the time.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A skilled lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial microexpressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast body and still emerging knowledge about deception, and it is clear that deception detection is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are adept at reading others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more “self-centered” lies while women tell more “other-centered” lies — usually to protect someone’s feelings — than married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "setting the benchmark data".
This helps provide a benchmark for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the vocal quality.
You need to know if someone is normally moving their feet all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when you see them moving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues to verbal and non-verbal misleading behaviors.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions are over.
Interviewers often falsely state that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Pay attention to the vocabulary of your topic.
Famous Scott Peterson drove off using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use distanced language: “I haven’t had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question altogether.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
