Climate Adversity Has Stifled the Economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled change, which generated high expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main economic indicators.
February's low temperatures, besides causing trillion-dollar losses to the agricultural sector, limited the state economy's opportunities for growth, causing overall economic activity to contract by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost affectations issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage to 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, peas and chirps.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state 18 percent, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the unemployment rate of the state during the first three quarters of the year 74 we observed an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 percent were unemployed in the second quarter, with an average rate of 4.53 percent of the active population.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who make dollars in an illicit way it is not easy for them to work to earn them, they invest them and use them in something," he says.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulties to find work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is worsened by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Aside from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the lag for the state is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinoan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat for Economic Affairs, the FDI of the State reached $630,697 from January to June, representing a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the previous $5,143,312 recorded in the same period of the year.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July at the public congress the approval of a loan of 3 trillion pesos, destined for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 trillion pesos in the sector and until November no profits were observed.
Reactions
For the representatives of the employer sector, the first year of Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
"The performance of the economy of Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensively to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our effort, it was necessary to align the effort of all and above all the good work already synchronized of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events like the frosts at the beginning of the year held back the state economy and restricted its yield and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level e flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities with more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we think it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is more inclusive, what I can say is that a lot of work has been done and the government is aware that there is still a lot to be done," he said.
