Debts to contributions to works
Works of a social nature contemplated in programs such as Habitat, Rescate de Espacios Públicos and 3x1 para migrantes risk not being finished or registering serious delays due to lack of economic resources, said Miguel <0xC3><0x81>ngel López Miranda.
The Director of Municipal Social Development indicated that although the construction programs have so far progressed, they are in a risky situation, because the State Government has not fulfilled its obligations to offer contributions in excess of 11 million pesos in the three programs.
He pointed out that in total, the investment of these three programs is approximately 50 million pesos, of which the State must provide 25 percent and so far only the Federation and the Municipality have provided resources for the works, therefore there is the possibility of a delay in their completion.
"They have to make a contribution of 12 million and despite the fact that the year is soon to end they have not given us anything, even if since July they had to give us a part of it," he said, "and we, in order not to register any delays, have started the works and we have advanced a lot, but we need the money."
He mentioned that last year, during the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padilla, the State had not paid the corresponding contributions, therefore at the beginning of the administration the Municipality had to request a credit to cover the 7 million that the State administration had not provided on that occasion.
“We had already experienced this in the previous six-year period because the state had not had the economic capacity to participate and the programs continue to operate and this year we, in order to have access to these programs, had to obtain the resources to cover what the state had not paid,” he said.
Despite the fact that there is a commitment on the part of the State authorities to provide these resources, he said that they had made the request to the Secretary of Administration and Finance, Armando Villarreal, to activate the management so that the corresponding percentages arrive as soon as possible.
“They have to provide almost 12 million and despite the fact that the year is coming to an end, they haven’t given us anything.”
The Court validates the "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals by digital ones is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft award, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, due to the fact that the radio and television regulations are an attribution reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favour of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions envisaged by it for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of ministers also resolved to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the minister-president said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also do not consider that it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the direction of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this translates into better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization that involves a decision in the public interest that does not only have a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompasses a group of powers that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded in some way the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative.
We analyze the possibility of a count "vote by vote" in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 trials.
In this sense, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize the local norms to the federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be remembered that Michoacán has not approved its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Act, at the same time that the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal deadline for this electoral process to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the deadlines laid down by the Law of the State.
On the same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms, because he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge" them.
Interviewed about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to make partial and total counts of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there are no minutes of voting and counting in the record of the urn is not found in the president of the urn; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all the ballot boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the supposed candidate winning the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the poll is equal to or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition of the representative of the party who presented the second candidate and/or co-presented the candidates.
The total count of the ballot may also be carried out if at the end of the joint count it follows that the difference between the supposedly winning candidate and that of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party from which the candidate came out second, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the Morelia election, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
