The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the verge of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet on Wednesday with Italy's president to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the verge of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in its majority of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former EU commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well drawn," he added.
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration headed by former EU commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Emphasizing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the volatility of the markets placed the yield of Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti formed.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti on Monday began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers’ groups and youth and women’s organizations.
He will finish his tour of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the Eurozone.
Monti said his government should persist until future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give it time to implement reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist that it should be trained only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
