Quinteto has included the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to perform in this country.
It is that bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The band is in the South American wing of its two-decade-long celebration tour and Sunday will make its only stopover in Central America.
That day will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles group The X and the Las Robertas nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I spent in Costa Rica only once the holidays; it is such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the previous days.
What is your message to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass until this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve offered over the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We offered two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and hopefully that set us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle; for both, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends always went surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; this is how we learned, through the people who love surfing.
When you saw the tour, you had huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is the reason for this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that’s why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to perform each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t performed in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and what we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
“First of all, I think none of us ever imagined we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it feel like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together excites us a lot.
We love each other and we love creating music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't get any better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are very close friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we are lucky to still be friends with all of them and it is an honor for us to be part of this Seattle sound that has emerged.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that’s a lot longer than a lot of bands normally last.
Firstly, I believe that we are all lucky to be alive, and secondly, we all care about each other.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give freedom to everyone to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity hasn’t been easy; however, thanks to your success, you’ve been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we don’t spend too much time touring because it’s easy to fall into this game of the great crowds and people who love your music.
