Why do you always change the lyrics of Yello Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
It is he who sings it and I believe he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
There are so many...
Among the first I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge up despite the fact that it is no longer in fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands that I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came up at the same time and, if that’s relevant now, I think it’s wonderful, because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had a more obscure content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting, because I think there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very obscure songs, even if they can sound a little positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
I think if you grow up and there’s a trauma in your life and you lose a relative or friend, these things start to influence your art and your music and these songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
I also think that we can also be happy and even like that we can make obscure music.
