Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results highlighted on the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost his life, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to try a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before the take-off of the aircraft, the pilot found that the climate conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the impact zone do not report the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In one research it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact occurred in a structural manner.
“The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, General Manager of Airports and Auxiliary Services assured that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Chiefs of Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and this happened on an ascending soft ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, the holder of the TBS, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced towards the area bordering DF and the State of Mexico, there were layers of low-height cloudiness.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought an area of lower height and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was neither loss of control nor alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the debris of the aircraft in a reduced zone:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The aircraft debris dispersion model makes it possible to assume that the helicopter crashed into the ground under structural integrity conditions.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the place of the accident there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the fieldwork, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope that ranged from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it possibly disarticulated along its path.
The information provides evidence that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful searching in an area wider than the encircled area around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security conducts an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the protocol 'Obesity Genetics of Children and Adolescents' which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Specialty Hospital of the 20th Century National Medical Center, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
Participants with or without rights are invited to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is provided to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 miners, the study will continue in the Unidad Sportiva Independencia (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Unidad Sportiva Morelos (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to diet.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family heredity history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (the aim is to identify people associated with childhood obesity) will be applied to all participants.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was a 77 per cent increase in obesity among boys and 47 per cent among girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American heredity, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the full evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they are overweight or obese.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors provide it in writing to the parents, explaining each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - corn flour meat dough wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fat and protein and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
The UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who has ensured that if the process of building and maintaining even the tar pavement is adequate, the cassis could be completely reduced or eliminated.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Blackcurrant, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, nearly 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the little stones that forms the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles pass through it, generating effort, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, these would spread better, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a last layer called a rolling layer is put, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the stresses, the bearing layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes blackcurrant.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that spoils is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrant and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to repair cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
