Thus was the work of the person from Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A typist from Cali has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a typist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", by confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week was the turn of "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has worked for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in typing, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is, the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigative team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant of the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galton magnifying glass, ink, a collector and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those on the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a typist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave to Eliazar González in a press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our work.
Typing is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can be crucial in resolving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identities of those captured.
When captured, many offenders present false ID cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search the database.
The researcher said that in one case of theft he had to remove a part of the wall of a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different robberies," he recalls.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a parent may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a print on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee he's the killer, it puts him on the crime scene.
A CTI typist explained that they extracted “fingerprints from objects with chemical or physical reagents.”
When they appear, a picker or tape is used to pick them up.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of the declinents, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers," said the CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything that is touched does not necessarily become a footprint.
It can be used, however, if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
'Indignants' defy authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters were marching in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part of the people acceded to the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement defied New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter Manhattan's Manhattan Square, where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another Big Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were storming out of Piazza Zuccotti, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order that allows the 'outraged' to camp again in that place, while the other part of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will settle in another place and continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the response of the 'outraged' to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Justice Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the place and allowing protesters to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'outraged' occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, owned by the parish Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some protesters, even if Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization claims that there are hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders traveled in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene on their behalf in front of the Police.
Meanwhile, the square Zuccotti - which is a privately owned precinct - remains closed pending the holding of a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analyzed.
Some of the displaced protesters carried and distributed copies of the court order at that time and even handed it over to the officers who were monitoring the square, which caused “some small clashes,” Bray said, denouncing the fact that some officials had beaten the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or enforcing “laws issued after the beginning of the occupation or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they previously used.”
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that because of this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, but warned that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councillor personally defended the early-dawn evacuation of Piazza Zuccotti, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the square because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to harm other people", because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
“This morning’s evacuation at dawn was disgusting and demonstrates that Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests of American workers than it is in defending the interests of American workers,” a spokesperson for the movement said, accusing the mayor of “not respecting freedom of expression.”
Occupy Wall Street officials also said they did not plan to hold "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two-month protests, which began on Sept. 17.
