Japan was reborn after the earthquake.
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, convalescing again after the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, Japan's worst disaster since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Government of Tokyo have estimated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to definitively turn the page: GDP rose by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualized rates.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% drop in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable rose 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo returned to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refuge values" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the unrest forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed the yen’s contribution for their weak results between July and September.
While markets continue their seats in outlying EU countries, the government of Yoshihiko Noda is not lowering its guard.
“We need to monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand’s floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said the majority of member countries had shown clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points of the global economy has highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
As it fell four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The Eurozone was even below the average, which is at level 100, dropping eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
Athens raises doubts again
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With peripheral risk premiums triggered and uncertainty reinstated in the parks, Greece continues to be entangled in the maze that leads to the exit from the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Hellenic Transitional Government is rather imposed by the demands of Brussels than by a real conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new prime minister, Lukas Papadimos yesterday pointed out that there is no alternative for structural reforms and that the period of a hundred days established in his appointment will perhaps be short to implement them, the leader of the conservative party New Democracy, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support the new elections in February.
"The main task of this government is to implement the decisions of the October 26 summit," Papadimos said when he opened a parliamentary debate yesterday that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the civil servant disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not cast doubt on his position: "We have committed ourselves to assisting the Transitional Government, but we have committed ourselves to nothing else."
The conservative leader has gone a step further in his pulse than the EU and IMF, the bodies that must unlock the $8,000 million Athens urgently needs, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to make the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact caused by the Papandreou referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock the aid if the new government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties do not sign "an unambiguous written commitment as soon as possible".
Economic Affairs spokesman Amadeu Altafaj said the troika inspectors would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new government "the necessary elements to pay the sixth tranche" of $8,000 million, even if there is no final date either.
The Greeks still have a lot to do.
