Spain "has reached a preponderant place at the global level in the role of Microfinance".
Queen Sofia recalled that in the last two decades the country has become the second-largest donor of the planet with regard to this instrument of cooperation whose "essence" lies in the fact that it is an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
The Queen inaugurated yesterday the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that these types of operations are "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Goals established by the United Nations for 2015, and, "very especially, in the one that has as its goal the reduction to half the volume of people who live with incomes under a dollar".
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in every corner of the planet, and assumes this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofia, who hoped that the initiatives and original contributions during the Summit, which will last until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women",
We have “achieved a lot of goals” and “we face a lot of challenges”.
The Microcredit Summit is seen not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which "two basic goals" must be promoted.
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the goal is that by the end of 2015 there are 175 million poor families who have accessed these financial services and that one hundred million of these families are emerging from the poverty line in which they now live.
The impulse in the design of microcredits in Spain and the rest of the world "followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, stressed Queen Sofia as an "act of justice and due recognition".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", whose work she has known since 15 years ago, when the Queen traveled to Bangladesh to learn about her loan policy on the ground.
