Jiménez said that microcredits require "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work under solidarity criteria and not let it be the victim of the cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded "the success" of giving "confidence" to those "excluded to whom everyone closes the door"; and the Mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed those present in a city that "opens its doors contaminated with a spirit of solidarity".
