The World According to Republican Presidential Candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry rival simplicity and ignorance.
Can a crisis-weakened America manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have multiplied the thunderous statements and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often unsupported - fuse.
Mitt Romney, best placed in the race for the nomination of the "Great Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and to question them "for manipulation of their currency", a theme bearer in an America exasperated by the migration of entire parts of its industry to Asia.
It doesn’t matter if it means a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate with a sophisticated foreign policy vision, nearly choked on an attitude that “flats” emotions.
