Nord Stream, Russia’s new gas gateway to Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe via a first 1,224 km tube linking the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And there is already talk of the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site feels like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland, in 1939.
That is to say if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in making its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, heavily gas-consuming Western countries whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us in an organic way," Fillon confirmed in inaugurating the pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-clad steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be abducted or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, that nothing interrupts over its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project leaders gave up on it when the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently set up off their coasts.
“In case of damage, we stop the gas passing in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to see a leak every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, one meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, he delivers precise information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 bars at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies created a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, the entire capacity of gas transport.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” said Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was 30% by the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their costs, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give back the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
Yet, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought an old and forgotten object to life, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand’s head at Modo Modo.
The success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robotic portrait of the buyer, because the notebook appeals to businessmen, students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its inception, now has almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her books in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center and has been able to impose her identity.
"We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a whole range of supports.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Employment Week for the Disabled begins today.
Despite a proactive public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, general manager of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
" The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before accessing employment.
They are quite old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that complicate the return to employment, and that "constitute the node of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That is the objective brakes.
There remains the unsaid, the mentalities that are evolving, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of the disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectually disabled".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the 6% employment target for disabled workers, set out in a law of 1987.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, general manager of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, increasing from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
